        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**1. What is a random variable in probability theory?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- A random variable is a variable whose value is a numerical outcome of a random phenomenon.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Tossing a coin and defining a variable X where X = 1 if it's heads and X = 0 if it's tails.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**2. What are the types of random variables?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- There are two main types of random variables: discrete and continuous.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Discrete: The number of cars passing a point on a highway in an hour (you can't have half a car).\n",
        "   \n",
        "* Continuous: The height of a person or the temperature of a room.\n",
        "\n",
        "-----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**3. What is the difference between discrete and continuous distributions?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Discrete distributions are for discrete random variables and continuous distributions are for continuous random variables. Discrete variables have countable values, while continuous variables can take any value within a range.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Discrete: A probability distribution of the number of heads in four coin flips.\n",
        "   \n",
        "* Continuous: A probability distribution representing the various heights of students in a class.\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**4. What are probability distribution functions (PDF)?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Probability Distribution Function (PDF) is a function that describes the likelihood of a continuous random variable taking on a given value.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* The curve representing the normal distribution, showing the probability of different values of a continuous variable.\n",
        "\n",
        "-----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**5. How do cumulative distribution functions (CDF) differ from probability distribution functions (PDF)?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The PDF gives the probability of a specific value, while the CDF gives the probability that a random variable takes on a value less than or equal to a given value.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* If you have a PDF for exam scores, the CDF would tell you the probability of scoring a certain score or lower.\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "#**6. What is a discrete uniform distribution?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- A discrete uniform distribution is a probability distribution where each possible value of the discrete random variable has an equal probability.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* The distribution of outcomes when rolling a fair die, where each number (1 to 6) has an equal chance of occurring.\n",
        "\n",
        "-----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**7. What are the key properties of a Bernoulli distribution?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The Bernoulli distribution is a discrete probability distribution for a random variable that has only two outcomes, usually labeled \"success\" and \"failure.‚Äù It is characterized by a single parameter, p, the probability of success.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Modeling whether a coin toss results in heads (success) or tails (failure).\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**8. What is the binomial distribution, and how is it used in probability?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The binomial distribution is a discrete probability distribution that describes the probability of a given number of successes in a fixed number of independent trials, each with the same probability of success.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Calculating the probability of getting exactly 7 heads in 10 coin flips.\n",
        "\n",
        "-------\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "#**9. What is the Poisson distribution and where is it applied?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The Poisson distribution is a discrete probability distribution that describes the probability of a given number of events occurring in a fixed interval of time or space, given a known average rate of occurrence. It is often used for rare events.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Modeling the number of emails received by a server per hour.\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**10. What is a continuous uniform distribution?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- A continuous uniform distribution is a probability distribution where all values within a given range are equally likely.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* A random number generator that selects any number between 0 and 1 with equal probability.\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**11. What are the characteristics of a normal distribution?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The normal distribution is a continuous probability distribution that is symmetric, bell-shaped, and characterized by its mean and standard deviation.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* The distribution of heights or weights in a large population.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**12. What is the standard normal distribution, and why is it important?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The standard normal distribution is a specific normal distribution with a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. It's important because any normal distribution can be transformed into it, allowing for easier calculations and comparisons.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Z-tables are based on the standard normal distribution, which are used to find probabilities for any normal distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**13. What is the Central Limit Theorem (CLT), and why is it critical in statistics?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The Central Limit Theorem (CLT) states that the distribution of the sum or average of a large number of independent and identically distributed random variables will be approximately normal, regardless of the original distribution's shape. It is critical because it allows us to make inferences about population parameters using sample statistics, and it underlies many statistical methods.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Even if a population is not normally distributed, the distribution of sample means taken from that population will be approximately normal if the sample size is large enough.\n",
        "\n",
        "-----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**14. How does the Central Limit Theorem relate to the normal distribution?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The Central Limit Theorem shows that the normal distribution arises naturally as the distribution of sample means, regardless of the shape of the original population distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* The CLT explains why many statistical tests and intervals rely on normal distribution theory.\n",
        "\n",
        "-----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**15. What is the application of Z statistics in hypothesis testing?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Z statistics are used in hypothesis testing to determine if a sample mean is significantly different from a population mean, when the population standard deviation is known.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Testing whether the average height of students in a sample is significantly different from the average height of students in a larger population, given the population standard deviation.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "-----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**16. How do you calculate a Z-score, and what does it represent?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- A Z-score is calculated by subtracting the population mean from a data point and dividing by the population standard deviation. It represents the number of standard deviations a data point is from the mean.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* A Z-score of 2 means the data point is 2 standard deviations above the mean.\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**17. What are point estimates and interval estimates in statistics?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- A point estimate is a single value used to estimate a population parameter, while an interval estimate provides a range of values within which the population parameter is likely to fall.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Point estimate: The sample mean is a point estimate of the population mean.\n",
        "   \n",
        "* Interval estimate: A confidence interval is an interval estimate for the population mean.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**18. What is the significance of confidence intervals in statistical analysis?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Confidence intervals provide a range within which the true population parameter is likely to lie, giving a measure of the uncertainty associated with the estimate.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* A 95% confidence interval means that we are 95% confident that the true population parameter lies within the interval.\n",
        "\n",
        "-----\n",
        "\n",
        "#**19. What is the relationship between a Z-score and a confidence interval?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Z-scores are used to calculate confidence intervals for population parameters when the population standard deviation is known.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Z-values determine the width of the confidence interval.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "-------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**20. How are Z-scores used to compare different distributions?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- Z-scores standardize data points, allowing for comparison of values from different normal distributions by measuring how far each value is from its respective mean in terms of standard deviations.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* Comparing a student's performance on two different tests with different scoring scales.\n",
        "\n",
        "-------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**21. What are the assumptions for applying the Central Limit Theorem?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The main assumptions for applying the Central Limit Theorem are that the sample must be sufficiently large (usually n ‚â• 30), and the observations must be independent and identically distributed.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* When taking multiple samples to estimate a population mean, each sample should be independent of the others and drawn from the same population.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**22. What is the concept of expected value in a probability distribution?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- The expected value is the average value one would expect to get if the random variable were to be repeated many times. It is calculated as the weighted average of all possible values, where the weights are the probabilities of those values.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* For a fair die, the expected value is 3.5.\n",
        "\n",
        "------\n",
        "\n",
        "#**23. How does a probability distribution relate to the expected outcome of a random variable?**\n",
        "\n",
        "- A probability distribution describes all possible outcomes of a random variable and their associated probabilities, allowing us to calculate the expected value, which is the long-run average outcome.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Example:**\n",
        "\n",
        "* The probability distribution of returns on a stock can be used to calculate the expected return, which is the average return an investor can expect over the long term.\n",
        "\n",
        "------"
      ],

        "# 3. Write a Python function to calculate the probability distribution function (PDF) of a Bernoulli distribution. [cite: 19, 20, 21, 22, 23, 60, 61, 62, 63, 64]\n",
        "\n",
        "def bernoulli_pdf(x, p):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Calculates the PDF of a Bernoulli distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "    Args:\n",
        "        x: The outcome (0 or 1).\n",
        "        p: Probability of success (1).\n",
        "\n",
        "    Returns:\n",
        "        The probability of the outcome.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    if x == 1:\n",
        "        return p\n",
        "    elif x == 0:\n",
        "        return 1 - p\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        return 0  # Probability is 0 for any other value\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example usage\n",
        "probability_of_1 = bernoulli_pdf(1, 0.6)\n",
        "print(\"P(X=1):\", probability_of_1)\n",
        "probability_of_0 = bernoulli_pdf(0, 0.6)\n",
        "print(\"P(X=0):\", probability_of_0)"

        "# 6. Write a Python program to calculate and plot the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of a discrete uniform distribution. [cite: 24, 25]\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Define the range\n",
        "low = 1\n",
        "high = 6  # Example range\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate the distribution\n",
        "x = np.arange(low, high + 1)\n",
        "cdf = np.cumsum([1 / len(x)] * len(x))  # Calculate CDF\n",
        "\n",
        "# Plot the CDF\n",
        "plt.step(x, cdf, where='post', color='orange')\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Value\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"CDF\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Discrete Uniform Distribution CDF\")\n",
        "plt.show()"

        "# 9. Write a Python function to calculate Z-scores from a dataset and plot them. [cite: 27]\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "def calculate_and_plot_z_scores(data):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Calculates Z-scores and plots them.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    mean = np.mean(data)\n",
        "    std_dev = np.std(data)\n",
        "    z_scores = (data - mean) / std_dev\n",
        "\n",
        "    plt.plot(z_scores, color='royalblue')\n",
        "    plt.xlabel(\"Data Point Index\")\n",
        "    plt.ylabel(\"Z-score\")\n",
        "    plt.title(\"Z-scores\")\n",
        "    plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example usage:\n",
        "data = np.array([1, 2, 3, 4, 5])\n",
        "calculate_and_plot_z_scores(data)"
      ],

        "# 10. Implement the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) using Python for a non-normal distribution. [cite: 28]\n",
        "\n",

        "# 18. Write a Python program to calculate the Z-score for a given data point and compare it to a standard normal distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
        "\n",
        "def calculate_and_compare_z_score(data_point, data):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Calculates the Z-score for a data point and compares it to the standard normal distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "    Args:\n",
        "        data_point: The data point to calculate the Z-score for.\n",
        "        data: The dataset.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    mean = np.mean(data)\n",
        "    std_dev = np.std(data)\n",
        "    z_score = (data_point - mean) / std_dev\n",
        "\n",
        "    print(\"Data Point:\", data_point)\n",
        "    print(\"Z-score:\", z_score)\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Compare with standard normal distribution\n",
        "    p_value = norm.cdf(z_score)  # Probability of getting a value less than or equal to Z\n",
        "    print(\"P-value (one-tailed, left):\", p_value)\n",
        "    print(\"P-value (one-tailed, right):\", 1 - p_value)\n",
        "    print(\"P-value (two-tailed):\", 2 * min(p_value, 1 - p_value))\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example:\n",
        "data = np.array([70, 85, 90, 60, 75, 80])\n",
        "data_point = 88\n",
        "calculate_and_compare_z_score(data_point, data)"

        "# 19. Implement hypothesis testing using Z-statistics for a sample dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
        "\n",
        "def z_test(sample_mean, pop_mean, pop_std, sample_size, alpha=0.05, alternative='two-sided'):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Performs a Z-test for hypothesis testing.\n",
        "\n",
        "    Args:\n",
        "        sample_mean: The mean of the sample.\n",
        "        pop_mean: The hypothesized population mean.\n",
        "        pop_std: The population standard deviation.\n",
        "        sample_size: The size of the sample.\n",
        "        alpha: Significance level (default is 0.05).\n",
        "        alternative: Type of test ('two-sided', 'less', or 'greater').\n",
        "\n",
        "    Returns:\n",
        "        The Z-statistic and the p-value.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    z_statistic = (sample_mean - pop_mean) / (pop_std / np.sqrt(sample_size))\n",
        "    if alternative == 'two-sided':\n",
        "        p_value = 2 * (1 - norm.cdf(np.abs(z_statistic)))\n",
        "    elif alternative == 'less':\n",
        "        p_value = norm.cdf(z_statistic)\n",
        "    elif alternative == 'greater':\n",
        "        p_value = 1 - norm.cdf(z_statistic)\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        raise ValueError(\"alternative must be 'two-sided', 'less', or 'greater'\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    return z_statistic, p_value\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example:\n",
        "sample_mean = 105\n",
        "pop_mean = 100\n",
        "pop_std = 15\n",
        "sample_size = 30\n",
        "alpha = 0.05\n",
        "\n",
        "z_stat, p_val = z_test(sample_mean, pop_mean, pop_std, sample_size)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Z-statistic:\", z_stat)\n",
        "print(\"P-value:\", p_val)\n",
        "\n",
        "if p_val < alpha:\n",
        "    print(\"Reject the null hypothesis.\")\n",
        "else:\n",
        "    print(\"Fail to reject the null hypothesis.\")"
      ],

        "# 20. Create a confidence interval for a dataset using Python and interpret the result.\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
        "\n",
        "def calculate_confidence_interval(data, confidence_level=0.95):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Calculates the confidence interval for a dataset.\n",
        "\n",
        "    Args:\n",
        "        data: A list or numpy array of numerical data.\n",
        "        confidence_level: The desired confidence level (e.g., 0.95 for 95%).\n",
        "\n",
        "    Returns:\n",
        "        A tuple containing the lower and upper bounds of the confidence interval.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    sample_mean = np.mean(data)\n",
        "    sample_std = np.std(data, ddof=1)  # Sample standard deviation (ddof=1 for unbiased)\n",
        "    sample_size = len(data)\n",
        "    z_value = norm.ppf((1 + confidence_level) / 2)  # Z-value for the given confidence level\n",
        "\n",
        "    margin_of_error = z_value * (sample_std / np.sqrt(sample_size))\n",
        "    lower_bound = sample_mean - margin_of_error\n",
        "    upper_bound = sample_mean + margin_of_error\n",
        "\n",
        "    return lower_bound, upper_bound\n",
        "\n",
        "# Example:\n",
        "data = np.array([22, 25, 28, 23, 27, 24, 26])\n",
        "confidence_interval = calculate_confidence_interval(data)\n",
        "print(\"Confidence Interval:\", confidence_interval)"

        "# 21. Generate data from a normal distribution, then calculate and interpret the confidence interval for its mean.\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from scipy.stats import norm\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate data\n",
        "data = np.random.normal(loc=50, scale=10, size=100)  # Example: mean=50, std_dev=10\n",
        "\n",
        "# Function to calculate confidence interval\n",
        "def confidence_interval_normal_mean(data, confidence_level=0.95):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Calculates the confidence interval for the mean of a normally distributed dataset.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    mean = np.mean(data)\n",
        "    std_err = np.std(data, ddof=1) / np.sqrt(len(data))  # Standard error of the mean\n",
        "    z_value = norm.ppf((1 + confidence_level) / 2)\n",
        "    margin_of_error = z_value * std_err\n",
        "    lower_bound = mean - margin_of_error\n",
        "    upper_bound = mean + margin_of_error\n",
        "    return (lower_bound, upper_bound)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculate the confidence interval\n",
        "confidence_interval = confidence_interval_normal_mean(data)\n",
        "print(\"Confidence Interval:\", confidence_interval)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Interpretation:\n",
        "print(\"\\nInterpretation:\")\n",
        "print(f\"The {95}% confidence interval for the mean is between {confidence_interval[0]:.2f} and {confidence_interval[1]:.2f}.\")\n",
        "print(\"This means that if we were to take many samples and calculate a confidence interval for each,\")\n",
        "print(\"we would expect the true population mean to lie within this interval in 95% of the cases.\")"

        "# 26. Calculate the range and interquartile range (IQR) of a dataset generated from a normal distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from scipy.stats import iqr\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate a dataset\n",
        "data = np.random.normal(loc=10, scale=4, size=100)  # Example normal distribution\n",

        "# Calculate the range\n",
        "data_range = np.max(data) - np.min(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculate the IQR\n",

        "\n",
        "# Print the results\n",
        "print(\"Range:\", data_range)\n",
        "print(\"Interquartile Range (IQR):\", data_iqr)"

        "# 27. Implement Z-score normalization on a dataset and visualize its transformation.\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate a dataset\n",
        "data = np.array([10, 12, 15, 18, 20, 25, 11, 14])  # Example dataset\n",
        "\n",
        "# Implement Z-score normalization\n",
        "def z_score_normalize(data):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Normalizes a dataset using Z-score normalization.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    mean = np.mean(data)\n",
        "    std_dev = np.std(data)\n",
        "    z_scores = (data - mean) / std_dev\n",
        "    return z_scores\n",
        "\n",
        "normalized_data = z_score_normalize(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Visualize the transformation\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)\n",
        "plt.plot(data, label='Original Data', marker='o')\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Data Point Index\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Value\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Original Data\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)\n",
        "plt.plot(normalized_data, label='Z-score Normalized Data', marker='o', color='orange')\n",
        "plt.xlabel(\"Data Point Index\")\n",
        "plt.ylabel(\"Z-score\")\n",
        "plt.title(\"Z-score Normalized Data\")\n",
        "plt.legend()\n",
        "\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Original Data:\", data)\n",
        "print(\"Z-score Normalized Data:\", normalized_data)"
      ],

        "# 28. Write a Python function to calculate the skewness and kurtosis of a dataset generated from a normal distribution.\n",
        "\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "from scipy.stats import skew, kurtosis\n",
        "\n",
        "# Generate a dataset\n",
        "data = np.random.normal(loc=5, scale=2, size=1000)  # Example normal distribution\n",
        "\n",
        "# Function to calculate skewness and kurtosis\n",
        "def calculate_skew_kurtosis(data):\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    Calculates the skewness and kurtosis of a dataset.\n",
        "    \"\"\"\n",
        "    data_skewness = skew(data)\n",
        "    data_kurtosis = kurtosis(data)\n",
        "    return data_skewness, data_kurtosis\n",
        "\n",
        "# Calculate skewness and kurtosis\n",
        "skewness_value, kurtosis_value = calculate_skew_kurtosis(data)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Print the results\n",
        "print(\"Skewness:\", skewness_value)\n",
        "print(\"Kurtosis:\", kurtosis_value)"
      ],
